Introduction¶

This is a Portfolio Project from 100 Days of Code: The Complete Python Pro Bootcamp.

This dataset was scraped from nextspaceflight.com and includes all the space missions since the beginning of Space Race between the USA and the Soviet Union in 1957.

Data Cleaning - Check for Missing Values and Duplicates¶

Looking at our dataset and the datatypes we are working with, we can see there are 2 columns that we won't need during our analysis ('Unnamed: 0.1' and 'Unnamed: 0'). The column 'Date' and 'Price' are also marked as a wrong type, that's why:

  • We remove the 2 columns containing unnecessary data.
  • Change the 'Date' column's type into datetype.
  • Change the 'Price' column's type from string to numeric.

Use a Choropleth Map to Show the Number of Launches by Country¶

To use the Choropleth Map we need to get hold of the country where the launches took place. We can obtain that information by splitting the 'Location' column.

After that we need to change some of the names in our new 'Country' column:

  • Russia is the Russian Federation
  • New Mexico should be USA
  • Yellow Sea refers to China
  • Shahrud Missile Test Site should be Iran
  • Pacific Missile Range Facility should be USA
  • Barents Sea should be Russian Federation
  • Gran Canaria should be USA

Lastly we need the 3 digit ISO country code to use as our location on the map.

In [30]:
df_data['Country'] = df_data.Location.str.split(',').str[-1]
In [31]:
df_data['Country'] = df_data['Country'].str.replace('Russia', 'Russian Federation')
df_data['Country'] = df_data['Country'].str.replace('New Mexico', 'USA')
df_data['Country'] = df_data['Country'].str.replace('Yellow Sea', 'China')
df_data['Country'] = df_data['Country'].str.replace('Shahrud Missile Test Site', 'Iran')
df_data['Country'] = df_data['Country'].str.replace('Pacific Missile Range Facility', 'USA')
df_data['Country'] = df_data['Country'].str.replace('Barents Sea', 'Russian Federation')
df_data['Country'] = df_data['Country'].str.replace('Gran Canaria', 'USA')
In [32]:
df_data.Country = df_data.Country.str.strip()
In [ ]:
df_data = clean_country(df_data, "Country", output_format="alpha-3")
In [34]:
launches_per_country = df_data.groupby(['Country', 'Country_clean'], as_index=False).agg({'Location': pd.Series.count})
In [35]:

In [37]:

fig.show()
fig.write_html('3Number of Launches per Country.html')

We can see that most launches (1398) took place in Russian Federation, followed by the USA with 1351 launches. The third country with the biggest number of launches is Kazakhstan with 701.

We can observe that the year 1971 was the most active with the number of launches reaching just under 120. The second most active year was 2018. Our dataset starts at 1957 and it was also the year with the smallest amount of launches.

The first big growth in launch numbers happened from 1959 to 1962, then the number dropped sharply for one year and continued to increase again. The years from 1965 and 1978 were definitely the most active. After that we saw a fairly big decline and it took until 2016 for the numbers to reach similar levels again. We saw the numbers fall in 2020 again and that's where our dataset ends.

plt.grid(color='grey', linestyle='--')
plt.show()

We can see that the most popular months tend to change every few years. However, December was the most active month for the biggest amount of years. With the least popular months for launches the change is not as frequent and January was at the bottom most often.

Cold War Space Race: USA vs USSR¶

We're going to compare the numbers of space missions between USA and USSR during the cold war. The cold war lasted from 1947 until 1991. Our dataset starts in 1957 so we won't have the complete data, however we will be able to analyse the majority of the cold war launches.

We must manipulate our dataset a little bit in order to obtain this information. We'll have to change some of the countries to USSR to correspond with the former Soviet states.

There are 15 post-Soviet states in total: Armenia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Estonia, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Latvia, Lithuania, Moldova, Russia, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan, Ukraine, and Uzbekistan.

We will also filter our dataset to make sure it only shows information up until 1991.

In [66]:
def change_location_iso(iso):
  ussr_countries = ['RUS', 'KAZ', 'BLR', 'EST', 'UKR', 'KGZ', 'AZE', 'MDA', 'UZB', 'TKM', 'GEO', 'ARM', 'TJK']
  if iso == 'USA':
      return 'USA'
  elif iso in ussr_countries:
      return 'USSR'
  else:
      return None
In [67]:
cold_war_df = df_data.copy()
In [68]:
cold_war_df['Country_clean'] = cold_war_df['Country_clean'].apply(change_location_iso)
In [69]:
cold_war_df = cold_war_df.loc[(cold_war_df['Year'] >= 1957) & (cold_war_df['Year'] <= 1991)]
In [70]:
cold_war_launches = cold_war_df.Country_clean.value_counts()
In [71]:

Out[78]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7ad2e1364700>]

We can see that most failures happened between 1958 and 1971, twice in those years we saw the numbers reach 20. From 1971 till 1976 we saw a good decline and the number failures fell under 5 a year. Since then the number of failures mostly stayed at or under 5 a year with the exeception of 1999, 2017, 2019 and 2020. We've never had a year with 0 failures.

Mission Status Comparison over Time¶

Now we are going to compare the four different types of mission status we have in our dataset: Success, Failure, Partial Failure and Prelaunch Failure.

In [79]:
failure_vs_success = df_data.groupby(['Year', 'Mission_Status']).size().reset_index(name='Amount')
In [80]:
pivot_failure_vs_success = failure_vs_success.pivot(index='Year', columns='Mission_Status', values='Amount')
In [81]:
plt.figure(figsize=(16,10))
plt.xticks(fontsize=14)
plt.yticks(fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=14)
plt.ylabel('Number of Launches', fontsize=14)
plt.title('Mission Status Comparison Year-on-Year', fontsize=18)
plt.grid(color='grey', linestyle='-')
plt.plot(pivot_failure_vs_success.index, pivot_failure_vs_success['Failure'], color='red', marker='o')
plt.plot(pivot_failure_vs_success.index, pivot_failure_vs_success['Partial Failure'], color='orange', marker='.')
plt.plot(pivot_failure_vs_success.index, pivot_failure_vs_success['Prelaunch Failure'], color='black', marker='^')
plt.plot(pivot_failure_vs_success.index, pivot_failure_vs_success['Success'], color='green', marker='s')

plt.legend(['Failure', 'Partial Failure', 'Prelaunch Failure', 'Success'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

Luckily there was only one year (1958) in our dataset when the number of failures exceeded the number of successful missions. We can also see that Prelaunch failures are not very common and only happened 4 times. The vast majority of missions ends successfully.

For Every Year Show which Country was in the Lead in terms of Total Number of Launches up to and including including 2020¶

In [85]:

In [87]:

plt.yticks(fontsize=14)
plt.xlabel('Year', fontsize=14)

From 1958 to 1962 USA was the leading country for the total number of launches per year. In 1963 Kazakhstan (which was then part of the USSR) and Russian Federation took over and were in the lead until 1993. From 1993 till 2020 we have 3 countries alternating the leader's position: USA, France and China. With USA in the lead for 13 years in total, France 6 and China 7.
